Yes, the president of the United States does know how to sign
his name. Defeating gridlock and temporarily defeating civil
rights groups, President Clinton and the Republican-controlled
Congress passed the long-awaited telecommunications bill last
week. '

As things usually go with the federal government, this bill is
far from simple and deals with a lot more than one item. It’s
filled with all sorts of goodies, including the V-chip.

There is a lot of talk about what children should and shouldn’t
be watching on television. Groups blame TV violence for
everything from schoolyard fights to serial murder. Television,
they argue, is such a major component in children’s lives that
what children see is often what they do. The movie The
Program was blamed for the deaths of more than one person
who tried to act out a scene from the ﬂick.

Those groups are the ones who lobbied extensively for some
way to monitor what our children are watching, and now they
have it. The miraculous V-chip is a little device which is
installed directly into TV sets in order to allow parents to con-
trol what comes onto the magic little screen. Similar to the way
channels can already be blocked out of cable boxes, now specif-
ic programs labelled with a certain violence rating can be auto-
matically blocked out.

In theory, th-is is ii good thing. There are, to put it simply,
some things children shouldn’t be -watching. However, this
leaves the question of what is and what is not violence up to the
discretion of an unknown agent. Responsibility is removed from
parents, who are the only people who should be monitoring the
TV—viewing habit/s of children. The V-chip is just one more
piece of parental responsibility lifted from the backs of parents
and taken on by tlie federal government.

_Another aspect {of the telecommunications bill which presents
problems is the set of restrictions placed on “pomography” over
the Internet. There is, according to the United States Supreme
Court, no official definition of pornography. But whatever it is,
you’d better not send it over the Internet. This has the potential
to include personal communications between two people. If you
send your boy/girlfriend a sexual message, Big‘Brother might
just see it and arrest you for violating the telecommunications
bill. /

One group speciﬁcally annoyed with the bill is the abortion-
rights group. There is a possibility’ that parts of the bill will
make it illegal for those groups to post information regarding
abortion on Internet bulletin boards. The information might be
considered offensive or indecent, so off the Internet it goes.

The government, in one swoop of a pen, just gave itself the
power to say what is and what is not appropriate (without letting
anyone else in on the secret) for us to see. The scope of the
telecommunications bill is frightening. The exact limitations
imposed by the bill are unclear, and that lack of clarity is what
makes it dangerous to civil rights. 4

