Are we safe from thetpolice?

Having been raised in the
sedate suburbs of Philadelphia,
I was always fed the image of
police officers as friendly, car-
ing folks. They captured the
bad guys, and they did it with a
wave and a smile to the honest
citizens they served.

Along with most of the other
illusions of my youth, this
vision of the officer‘ as Blue
Knight has been rudely dis-
placed. How could it be other-
wise, ’ with the barrage of
images before us? King,
Gainmage, Antantis —— victims
of brutal beatings. An innocent
Atlanta civilian crawling away
from a gunfight and pleading
for mercy. as plainclothes offi-
cers shoot him to death. The
unﬂinching racism of Mark
Fuhrman. Massive scandals
within Philadelphia, New
Orleans and other cities which
have brought thousands of con-

_ .victions into question.

It is a problem extending far
beyond the sensational cases
plastered across the front page
or the evening news. It reaches
into the streets, homes and

' lives of every one of us.

It‘ extends to an ofﬁcer who
called me and a group of
friends “assholes” and told us
to “Go the f*** home.”
(Excuse me, officer, but I
didn’t know it was illegal to
walk down a street after 2 a.m.)
To cops at a Steeler’s game
who mercilessly berated con-
fused fans. (They hadmade the
mistake of stopping some-
where they didn’t belong to
watch a play.) Toa fellow stu-
dent who found herself sur-
rounded by three police cruis-
ers, lights ﬂashing and sirens
blaring, at 9:00 a.m.
(Obviously, failure to come to
a complete halt at a stop sign is
the mark of a dangerous criini—
na1.)’

Nearly everyone seems to
have a story of unreasonable

treatment by the police. Many _

think little of it; perhaps it is
what we have come to expect.

Greg
Marchand

Is it now normal for cops to be
rude and confrontational?
It seems that a venomous

attitude has set in among our .

police today. All too often,
officers appear to have aban-
doned attempts at enforcing the
law by conventional means.
Their method of operation is
no longer to protect and to
serve, but to demand respect
through fear. _

It is a vicious method which
has sucked police departments
into an abyss of racism, brutali-
ty and hatred. ‘

How did this happen? How
did the honest, caring officer of
yesterday turn into the “pig” of
today? The issues run far too
deep for explication within a
short, subjective column, but I
can wager a few guesses.

I would begin with the
motorization of the police
force. Putting a cop in a car
seems like a good move; it
enhances mobility and allows a
quicker response to emergency

"situations. However, it also

removes officers from the com-
munity they need to become a
part of, turning them into
nameless faces, badges and
guns within intimidating
mobile fortresses. How often
do you see officers smile and
wave from behind the wheel?
As the concept of the “beat
cop” has faded away, officers
have lost any bond they had
with the everyday public.

The community itself has
done its share to deepen the
schism. Disorderly urban envi-
ronments have been breeding
grounds for the bacteria within
our law enforcement and jus-
tice systems. The insistence of

our political leaders upon -

absurd “wars” against drugs,
underage drinking, prostitution
and other non-violent offenses
has siphoned off the manpower
and funding necessary to com-
bat real crime. Urban disorder

cannot be reversed by manda-
tory sentencing, capital punish-
ment, welfare reform or any
other simplistic solutions
which ignore the stark realities
of economic degradation.
Burdened by impossible
mandates and mounting pres-
sures, it was probably
inevitable that the minor ail-
ments within law enforcement
turned into a full-blown epi-
demic.-Corruption and con-
frontation have become the
norms among police depart-

ments, and we must seek new ‘

cures. I would venture the fol-
lowing as possible starting
points.

The dual principles of “to
protect” and “to serve” should

guide law enforcement. Take.

more cops out of their cars and
put them on foot or on bikes.
Trainofficers to interact with

‘the general public in a more

positive manner; ' mutual
respect is a lot more conducive
to order than respect based on
fear and distrust. Enforce stan-
dards among our cops —— it is
difficult to place much trust in
an ofﬁcer who carmot police a
waistline, let alone chase down
a thug. Finally, begin to change
the absurd laws which waste
the efforts of our law-enforce-
ment community on non-vio-
lent offenses.

The catalysts for new
approaches in law enforcement
must be found in the combined
efforts of officers, politicians
and the public. Programs like
Community Oriented Policing

and review boards are positive‘

trends and should be ‘expanded.
Kept in the public eye and
given a chance to pursue a
more reasonable definition of
crime, police departments will
undergo a change for the better.

The job of the Blue Knight is
a demanding one, far too often

glorified or vilified beyond I

reality. It is time to bring our
cops back down to earth.

Greg Marchand is platming to

stay out of trouble for a while.

